SIMPLE: incise
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Incise
<hw>In*cise"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Incised</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Incising</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>incisus</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>incidere</ets> to incise: cf. F. <ets>inciser</ets>. See
<er>Incide</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To cut in or into with a sharp instrument; to carve;
to engrave.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I on thy grave this epitaph <qex>incise</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>T.
Carew.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cut, gash, or wound with a sharp instrument; to
cut off.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incised</ent>⟦br⟧
